{"session_id":"svc-1778116390596466141","seq":0,"type":"session.start","ts":"2026-05-07T01:13:10.794400525Z","data":{"provider":"","model":"gpt-5.4-mini","resolved_harness":"codex","harness_source":"auto_route","resolved_model":"gpt-5.4-mini","work_dir":"/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-c14f6525-20260507T011308-39144c36","max_iterations":0,"prompt":"\u003cexecute-bead\u003e\n  \u003cinstructions\u003e\nYou are executing one bead inside an isolated DDx execution worktree. The bead\u0026#39;s \u0026lt;description\u0026gt; and \u0026lt;acceptance\u0026gt; are the completion contract — every AC must be provably satisfied by a specific code, test, or file you can point to after your commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Step 0: size check\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;The bead is too big when any of these holds:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- More than ~6 ACs spanning unrelated subsystems.\u0026#xA;- AC mixes design, implementation, integration tests, and docs as separate top-level deliverables.\u0026#xA;- Description names multiple feature-sized sub-pieces.\u0026#xA;- More than ~500 lines across more than ~5 files in unrelated packages.\u0026#xA;- If the bead description exceeds 8000 bytes, treat Step 0 as a split-first pass and favor child-bead scoping before implementation.\u0026#xA;- Auto-decomposition is capped at depth 2: root beads may split once, decomposed children may split once more, and third-level splits must be rejected with an explanation.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;If too big, decompose — do not attempt the work:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;1. `ddx bead create` for each child slice (focused title, description, AC; copy parent\u0026#39;s labels and spec-id).\u0026#xA;2. `ddx bead dep add \u0026lt;child-id\u0026gt; \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt;` to record edges.\u0026#xA;3. `ddx bead update \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt; --notes \u0026#39;decomposed into \u0026lt;child-ids\u0026gt;\u0026#39;` so the decomposition is visible.\u0026#xA;4. Write `.ddx/executions/20260507T011308-39144c36/no_changes_rationale.txt` listing each child ID and slice, then stop.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;A clean decomposition is a successful attempt. Do not mix partial implementation with decomposition.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## How to work\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Read first. If the bead names files, specs, or prior beads, read them before editing — do not guess.\u0026#xA;- Cross-reference each AC against concrete evidence (test name, file path, function) before committing. If you cannot point at it, it is not done.\u0026#xA;- Run the project\u0026#39;s test and lint commands before committing. **Do not commit red code** — fix failures first.\u0026#xA;- Stage with `git add \u0026lt;specific-paths\u0026gt;`; never `git add -A` (the worktree may have unrelated WIP).\u0026#xA;- Commit exactly once when green; conventional-commit subject ending with `[\u0026lt;bead-id\u0026gt;]`. Stop after the commit.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s scope.\u0026#xA;- If you cannot finish, write `.ddx/executions/20260507T011308-39144c36/no_changes_rationale.txt` (what is done, what blocks, what a follow-up needs) before exiting. No commit and no rationale ⇒ DDx records `no_evidence_produced`. A well-justified no_changes beats a bad commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## no_changes contract\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;If you write `.ddx/executions/20260507T011308-39144c36/no_changes_rationale.txt`, it MUST carry one of:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- `verification_command: \u0026lt;one-line shell command\u0026gt;` — the loop runs it (cwd = project root, 60s); exit 0 closes the bead, non-zero rejects.\u0026#xA;- `status: needs_investigation` + `reason: \u0026lt;why\u0026gt;` — bead stays open for triage.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Bare rationales (\u0026#34;nothing to do\u0026#34;) are rejected.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Reports\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Freestanding artifacts (investigation reports, findings docs) go under `.ddx/executions/20260507T011308-39144c36/` (the per-attempt evidence directory under `.ddx/executions/`). **Never write reports to `/tmp` or any path outside the repository** — out-of-repo paths are invisible to the post-merge reviewer and cause BLOCK on missing evidence. If the bead names a specific in-repo path, use it; else default to `.ddx/executions/20260507T011308-39144c36/\u0026lt;short-name\u0026gt;.md`. Stage and commit the report alongside code.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Bead overrides project defaults\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;The bead description and AC override CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, and conservative project defaults (YAGNI, DOWITYTD, no-docs-unless-asked) in this worktree — write whatever the bead asks for.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Review gate\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- The review is a gate, not an escape hatch — meet every AC in this pass.\u0026#xA;- Address every BLOCKING `\u0026lt;review-findings\u0026gt;` item; do not declare `no_changes` with blocking findings open.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Constraints\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Work only inside this execution worktree.\u0026#xA;- Keep `.ddx/executions/` intact — DDx uses it as execution evidence.\u0026#xA;- **Never run `ddx init`** — the workspace is initialized; running it corrupts the bead queue.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s named scope.\u0026#xA;- Do not rewrite CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, or other project-instructions files unless the bead asks.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## When the work is done\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;After the commit succeeds and every AC is verified, stop. Return control to the orchestrator — do not keep exploring or testing.\n  \u003c/instructions\u003e\n  \u003cbead id=\"ddx-c14f6525\"\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003ework: evaluate completed epics for closure\u003c/title\u003e\n    \u003cdescription\u003e\nPROBLEM\u0026#xA;`ddx work` currently reports dependency-ready epics only as structural skips. That is correct for epics with open child work, but stale for epics whose direct children are all closed. Operators then have to manually notice and close completed epics, and the no-ready-work diagnostic keeps showing noise.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;ROOT CAUSE WITH FILE:LINE\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/bead/store.go:1416 appends every ordinary epic container to ReadyExecutionBreakdown.SkippedEpics.\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/bead/store.go:1482 filters ordinary epic containers out of ReadyExecution entirely.\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/bead/store.go:1696 defines isOrdinaryEpicContainer as true for any issue_type `epic`, without considering whether the epic has open children or only closed children.\u0026#xA;- cli/cmd/agent_cmd.go:1940-1942 renders all skipped epics with the same \u0026#34;epics are structural containers; decompose into tasks\u0026#34; message, so completed epics are not surfaced as closure candidates.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;PROPOSED FIX\u0026#xA;Teach the execution queue to distinguish epics with open children from epics whose direct children are all closed. `ddx work` should at least evaluate completed epics for closure instead of treating them as ordinary structural skips. A safe implementation may add an explicit closure-candidate classification and auto-close only when the epic acceptance/dependencies are satisfied by closed children; if auto-close is not safe, the text/JSON plan must clearly surface the epic as a closure candidate requiring operator action.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;IN-SCOPE FILES\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/bead/store.go\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/bead/gaps_test.go\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_loop.go\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_loop_test.go\u0026#xA;- cli/cmd/agent_cmd.go and/or cli/cmd/work_plan_test.go for operator-facing output\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;NON-SCOPE\u0026#xA;- Do not execute epics through the normal bead executor. Epics remain structural containers.\u0026#xA;- Do not close epics that still have any direct child whose status is not closed.\u0026#xA;- Do not implement recursive grandchild graph closure beyond the existing direct-child/dependency model unless a failing test proves it is required.\u0026#xA;- Do not change task queue priority ordering for ordinary executable tasks.\n    \u003c/description\u003e\n    \u003cacceptance\u003e\n1. TestReadyExecutionBreakdown_ClassifiesEpicClosureCandidates creates one epic with only closed direct children and one epic with an open direct child; the completed epic is not reported in SkippedEpics, while the active epic still is.\u0026#xA;2. TestExecuteBeadWorkerEvaluatesCompletedEpicForClosure proves `ddx work` does not dispatch the normal executor for an epic but does surface or close a completed epic through the new closure-evaluation path.\u0026#xA;3. TestWorkPlan_ShowsCompletedEpicClosureCandidate verifies `ddx work plan --json` or text output distinguishes completed-epic closure candidates from structural epics with open children.\u0026#xA;4. Existing TestExecuteBeadWorkerEpicIsNotOrdinaryWork remains green for epics with open children.\u0026#xA;5. cd cli \u0026amp;\u0026amp; go test ./internal/bead/... ./internal/agent/... ./cmd/... -run \u0026#34;TestReadyExecutionBreakdown_ClassifiesEpicClosureCandidates|TestExecuteBeadWorkerEvaluatesCompletedEpicForClosure|TestWorkPlan_ShowsCompletedEpicClosureCandidate|TestExecuteBeadWorkerEpicIsNotOrdinaryWork\u0026#34; -count=1 passes.\u0026#xA;6. lefthook run pre-commit passes.\n    \u003c/acceptance\u003e\n    \u003clabels\u003ephase:2, area:agent, area:beads, area:cli, kind:bug, reliability, spec:FEAT-010\u003c/labels\u003e\n    \u003cmetadata parent=\"ddx-f3dfde0d\" spec-id=\"FEAT-010\" base-rev=\"638ce67c731cbf5e77599f5d0e577bb36de49486\" bundle=\".ddx/executions/20260507T011308-39144c36\"/\u003e\n  \u003c/bead\u003e\n  \u003cgoverning\u003e\n    \u003cref id=\"FEAT-010\" path=\"docs/helix/01-frame/features/FEAT-010-task-execution.md\"\u003eFeature: Task Execution\u003c/ref\u003e\n  \u003c/governing\u003e\n\u003c/execute-bead\u003e\n","metadata":{"attempt_id":"20260507T011308-39144c36","base_rev":"638ce67c731cbf5e77599f5d0e577bb36de49486","bead_id":"ddx-c14f6525","bundle_path":".ddx/executions/20260507T011